  <chapter id="Configuration_Utils">
    <title>Configuration Utilities</title>

    <sect1 id="CfgMgr2_Command_Line" role="nobrk">
      <title>Command Line Interface</title>

      <sect2 id="envchk">
        <title>ENVCHECK</title>

        <para><emphasis role="bold">envchk</emphasis> &lt;options&gt;
        environment_file</para>

        <para><informaltable colsep="1" frame="all" rowsep="1">
            <tgroup cols="2">
              <colspec colwidth="130.50pt" />

              <colspec />

              <tbody>
                <row>
                  <entry><emphasis>-d --schema-dir
                  &lt;path&gt;</emphasis></entry>

                  <entry>path to schema files. default
                  (/opt/HPCCSystems/componentfiles/configschema/xsd/)</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry><emphasis>-p --schema-plugins-dir
                  &lt;path&gt;</emphasis></entry>

                  <entry>path to plugin files, default (xsd/plugins/)</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry><emphasis>-m --master-config
                  &lt;filename&gt;</emphasis></entry>

                  <entry>name of master schema file, default
                  (environment.xsd)</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-l --level &lt;level&gt;</entry>

                  <entry>output level (and above), e=error, w=warning,
                  i=informational</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-v --verbose</entry>

                  <entry>verbose output</entry>
                </row>
              </tbody>
            </tgroup>
          </informaltable>The envcheck utility returns specified values for
        items relating to the environment configuration components.</para>

        <para>Example:</para>

        <programlisting>envchk -d /opt/HPCCSystems/componentfiles/configschema/xsd/ dali.xsd</programlisting>
      </sect2>

      <sect2 id="envchk" role="brk">
        <title>envmod</title>

        <para><emphasis role="bold">envmod &lt;options&gt;
        &lt;environment_file&gt;</emphasis> </para>

        <para>The envmod utility allows you to modify to the environment
        configuration components with the specified options.</para>

        <para>Examples: </para>

        <para><programlisting>envmod -d /opt/HPCCSystems/componentfiles/configschema/xsd/ dali.xsd
envmod -m NewEnvironment.xsd
</programlisting></para>

        <para><informaltable colsep="1" frame="all" rowsep="1">
            <tgroup cols="2">
              <colspec colwidth="130.50pt" />

              <colspec />

              <tbody>
                <row>
                  <entry><emphasis role="bold">Configuration
                  Options</emphasis></entry>

                  <entry></entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-d, --schema-dir </entry>

                  <entry>Specifies the path to schema files. Default value
                  <emphasis>p/opt/HPCCSystems/componentfiles/configschema/xsd/</emphasis></entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-p, --schema-plugins-dir</entry>

                  <entry>Specifies the path to plugin files. Default value
                  <emphasis>xsd/plugins/</emphasis></entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-m, --master-config</entry>

                  <entry>Specifies the name of the master schema file.
                  Defaults to <emphasis>environment.xsd</emphasis></entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry><emphasis role="bold">Execution
                  Options</emphasis></entry>

                  <entry></entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-t, --template </entry>

                  <entry>Required file path to the modification
                  template.</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-e, --env </entry>

                  <entry>Optional file path to environment file to modify.
                  Omit option to validate the modification template.</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>--inputs</entry>

                  <entry>Lists the template inputs. When specified, the
                  template inputs are listed and the command exits.</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>--input-file </entry>

                  <entry>Optional full path to a file with defined inputs for
                  the template. This would be combined with any command line
                  inputs.</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-i, --input &lt;var=value&gt;</entry>

                  <entry>Assigns the indicated value to the variable input.
                  The input must be defined in the template value. Use a comma
                  separated list (no blanks) for multi-value inputs. Inputs
                  given on the command line override any in an input file
                  (--input-file).</entry>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <entry>-o, --output </entry>

                  <entry>Optional. Specify to save as an output file. If
                  output file path is specified, results are written to the
                  specified file. If not specified, the input environment file
                  is overwritten. Omit the -o option to test the modification
                  template.</entry>
                </row>
              </tbody>
            </tgroup>
          </informaltable></para>
      </sect2>
    </sect1>
